Analyzing World Happines Data¶

By: Matthew McIntyre¶

In this tutorial, I will analyze data from the World Happiness Report for 2021. The World Happiness Report contains happiness rankings of countries around the world. The polling to collect the happiness data is done by Gallup and published in the Gallup World Poll (GWP). The GWP has a section about global happiness data called the "Gallup Global Happiness Center".

The goal of this tutorial is to analyze factors that affect the happiness in a country. During this tutorial, I will walk through the phases of the data science pipeline to help me analyze the data and derive useful insights from that analysis.

The above table is the education index from the Human Development Reports. On the Human Development Reports website, they provide the following definition: "Education index is an average of mean years of schooling (of adults) and expected years of schooling (of children), both expressed as an index obtained by scaling with the corresponding maxima." A higher score means more education. The table contains scores from 1990 to 2019 but some countries have no data for some years as you can see in the table. Click here to read more about the Human Development Reports. Click here to view the education index in full.

In [797]:
# map the country to the 2021 predicted score
edu_score_2021 = pd.Series(dtype = 'float32')

for country, info in education_index_df.groupby('Country'):
    # get scores and years from each country, ignoring years where the country has no score
    X = np.array(info.loc[info['Score'] != '..', 'Year'])
    y = np.array(info.loc[info['Score'] != '..', 'Score'])
    # use the year as a predictor for the score and make a prediction for the 2021 score using linear regression
    lin_model = LinearRegression()
    lin_model.fit(X.reshape(-1, 1), y)
    # make a scatter plot of year vs score for each country to see if the relationship is linear
    plt.figure(figsize = (3, 3))
    plt.scatter(X, y)
    plt.title(country)
    plt.show()
    # pair up the country with its 2021 predicted score in the Series object
    edu_score_2021.loc[country.strip()] = lin_model.predict(np.array(2021).reshape(1, -1))[0]

In the above code, I use the DataFrame groupby() method to loop through each country individually and make a linear regression predction for their 2021 education index score. I use the years to predict the score. I also produced a scatter plot for each country where year is on the x axis and the score is on the y axis. I did this to verify that there is a linear relationship beween year and score. The country and predicted 2021 score are paired up in a pandas Series object.

Now that I have the predicted scores for 2021, I can append these scores to my main table.

This is the table that I will use from now on in my analysis. I want to explain what each column header means.

Country name, Regional indicator: Self explanatory

Ladder score: The "happiness score". 0 being the least happy and 10 being the most happy.

Logged GDP per capita: The log of the gdp per capita. Gdp is the value of all goods and services produced by a country in some time period. Gdp per capita is gdp divided by the population of the country. A higher value is better for this attribute.

Social support: The national average of respones to the question: If you were in trouble, do you have relatives or friends you can count on to help you whenever you need them, or not?. This is a true or false question so answers are encoded with 1 and 0; 1 meaning true/yes and 0 meaning false/no

Health life expectancy: "Average number of years that a person can expect to live in "full health" by taking into account years lived in less than full health due to disease and/or injury". This definition is from the World Health Organization.

Freedom to make life choices: The national average of respones to the question: Are you satisfied or dissatisfied with your freedom to choose what you do with your life?. The response is binary so it can be encoded as 1 or 0 like the social support response

Perceptions of corruption: The national average of respones to the following questions: "Is corruption widespread throughout the government or not?" and "Is corruption widespread within businesses or not?". The response is binary so it can be encoded as 1 or 0

depression rate: The percentage of the population that is depressed.

2021 edu index: The 2021 prediction for the education index score for a country. The education index is explained in the data collection section at the beginning of the project.
